QuantMap Campaign Completion & State Semantics — Remediation Spec
Status: Spec for implementation
Date: 2026-04-11
Scope: Runtime state model, campaign completion semantics, operator-facing status, recompute paths
Explicitly out of scope: Smart Mode, Quick Tune, packaging, attribution engine, telemetry collection changes

1. Problem Framing
What is wrong with current completion semantics
QuantMap's campaign completion currently conflates three distinct events into a single state transition. At runner.py line 2306–2310:

with get_connection(_eff_db_path) as conn_final:
    conn_final.execute(
        "UPDATE campaigns SET status='complete', completed_at=? WHERE id=?",
        ...
    )

This fires when the measurement phase ends — all configs have run, all cycles have committed to the DB. After this write, _clear_progress() is called and the analysis/scoring/report pipeline runs. If that pipeline fails (line 2381–2385), the runner emits a console error and calls sys.exit(1). The DB already says complete.

The result: quantmap list shows a campaign as complete when in fact it may have no scores, no report, and no usable output. An operator looking at that campaign has no way to distinguish "fully done" from "measurement done, analysis failed" without opening the database or checking whether a report file exists on disk.

There is no persistent, queryable record of:

Whether analysis/scoring succeeded
Whether the report was generated
Whether run context was degraded
This is a trustworthiness problem. QuantMap's list output is the operator's first window into what happened. If that window cannot distinguish states that have meaningfully different implications for the operator's next action, it is misleading.

Why measurement success must be separated from analysis/report success
Measurement data — raw request results in raw.jsonl, telemetry rows in the telemetry table, cycle records — is committed continuously during the run. It is durable and authoritative. If a campaign's measurement phase completes cleanly, the data is good regardless of what happens afterward.

Analysis (scoring, elimination filtering) is a deterministic function of that data. If it fails, it can be rerun. It does not affect the quality or validity of the underlying measurements.

Report generation is presentation logic applied to the analysis results. It can fail due to template bugs, filesystem issues, or encoding problems entirely unrelated to measurement quality.

Treating these three as one thing — and presenting all three outcomes under a single complete status — obscures the actual situation. An operator who sees complete and no report should know immediately: analysis failed, measurement is safe, rerun the analysis. Currently they see complete and have to investigate manually.

Why degraded context must not invalidate direct measurements
Run context (from run_context.py, captured at cycle start) is an environmental quality assessment. It captures CPU/GPU state, background load, environment cleanliness. This information affects confidence in measurements — it does not invalidate the measurements themselves.

If run context capture fails (line 1475–1478 shows this is already handled gracefully as non-fatal), the cycle proceeds. The request outcomes and telemetry are unaffected. A degraded or missing context should be surfaced to the operator as a confidence qualifier, not treated as a failure that propagates to measurement validity.

Currently, context quality is captured to per-cycle JSON sidecar files ({config_id}_cycle{N:02d}_run_context.json) but is never aggregated, never stored in the DB, and never surfaced in list or reports. It is invisible to operators who do not manually inspect the result directory.

2. State Model: Concrete Layer Definitions
The three-layer model is adopted as-is but with concrete semantics for QuantMap:

Layer 1 — Authoritative Measurement State
Contents: requests table rows, telemetry table rows, background_snapshots rows, cycles table rows, configs table rows (status only: running/complete/oom/skipped_oom), raw.jsonl, telemetry.jsonl, campaign_start_snapshot.

Durability guarantee: Committed row-by-row during the run. Never rewritten after the fact. Loss of any Layer 1 data is unrecoverable without rerunning the campaign.

Truth boundary: A Layer 1 record is true at the moment it was written. It says what happened during measurement. It does not say what it means.

Invalidation rule: Layer 1 data can only be invalidated by the runner's own cycle invalidation logic (_mark_cycle_invalid()). External tools — analysis, scoring, attribution — must never modify Layer 1 data. They only read it.

Layer 2 — Derived Interpretation State
Contents: scores table rows (including elimination decisions), attribution_events table rows (when implemented), methodology_snapshots table rows.

Durability guarantee: Fully recomputable from Layer 1 at any time. Deletion of Layer 2 data is not data loss — it is a recomputation trigger.

Truth boundary: Layer 2 records reflect what the scoring/attribution rules said about Layer 1 data at the time they were generated. If rules change (e.g., governance thresholds are adjusted), Layer 2 can be regenerated with a different outcome. The underlying measurements did not change.

Recompute rule: Any Layer 2 generation failure is a recomputable failure — not a data loss event. The operator should be told this explicitly: "Measurement data is safe. Run quantmap rescore to regenerate scores and report."

Layer 3 — Presentation / Artifact State
Contents: Markdown reports, HTML reports, CSV exports, .qmap bundles, artifacts table rows, evidence report files.

Durability guarantee: Fully regeneratable from Layer 1 + Layer 2. Deletion is not data loss.

Truth boundary: Artifacts are a rendering of Layer 2 at a point in time. Regenerating them with updated Layer 2 produces a different artifact. The artifact is stamped with a generation timestamp.

Rerender rule: Any artifact generation failure is a rerендerable failure. It does not affect Layer 1 or Layer 2.

3. Campaign State Machine
Design constraints
The state machine must be implementable as an additive change to the existing schema
It must not break existing campaign rows in the DB
It must be readable by list, explain, and future status commands without complex logic
It must not overcomplicate the measurement-phase state machine (which already works correctly)
Proposed model
Retain the existing campaigns.status field for the measurement phase only. Its values and semantics are clarified, not changed:

status value	Meaning (clarified)
pending	Registered but measurement has not started
running	Measurement phase in progress
complete	Measurement phase finished. All configs have committed their final status. This says nothing about analysis or reports.
failed	Measurement phase ended in a fatal error. Some or all measurement data may be present but incomplete.
The word "complete" for campaigns.status is redefined going forward to mean measurement complete, not fully done. This is a semantic clarification, not a value change. Existing rows are unaffected.

Add two new status columns to campaigns to track the derived layers independently:

New column	Type	Values	Meaning
analysis_status	TEXT	NULL / 'complete' / 'failed'	Whether scoring/analysis has run and what happened
artifact_status	TEXT	NULL / 'complete' / 'failed'	Whether report generation has run and what happened
NULL in both columns for an existing complete campaign means "analysis was never tracked" (pre-migration rows). The list command handles this case explicitly.

Synthesized operator-facing status
list (and any future status command) synthesizes a display status from these three fields:

status	analysis_status	artifact_status	Display label
pending	—	—	pending
running	—	—	running
failed	—	—	failed
complete	NULL	NULL	measured (legacy or analysis not yet run)
complete	complete	NULL	scored (report pending or failed before tracking)
complete	complete	complete	complete
complete	failed	NULL	analysis-failed
complete	complete	failed	report-failed
The display label appears in list instead of the raw status value. The raw values remain in the DB for queryability.

Context degradation flag
Add one further column:

New column	Type	Values	Meaning
context_quality	TEXT	NULL / 'clean' / 'mostly_clean' / 'noisy' / 'distorted' / 'unavailable'	Worst context quality observed across cycles in this campaign
This is the worst-case quality tier from the run context assessment, aggregated at campaign completion time. It is a confidence qualifier, not a failure state. A campaign with context_quality = 'noisy' and artifact_status = 'complete' is fully valid — the operator is informed that the measurement environment was noisy.

State transition diagram (measurement phase — unchanged)
[start]
  → status='running' (campaign registered)
    → configs: status='running'
      → cycles: status='pending' → 'started' → 'complete'|'invalid'
    → configs: status='complete'|'oom'|'skipped_oom'
  → status='complete'  ← measurement boundary
  → analysis_status='complete'|'failed'  ← analysis boundary
  → artifact_status='complete'|'failed'  ← artifact boundary

  [interrupted] → status stays 'running' → resumable
  [fatal error] → status='failed' → may be resumable (see Section 7)

4. Data Model Implications
New DB migration: Migration 10
-- Add layered status tracking to campaigns
ALTER TABLE campaigns ADD COLUMN analysis_status TEXT DEFAULT NULL;
ALTER TABLE campaigns ADD COLUMN artifact_status TEXT DEFAULT NULL;
ALTER TABLE campaigns ADD COLUMN context_quality TEXT DEFAULT NULL;
ALTER TABLE campaigns ADD COLUMN analysis_failed_at TEXT DEFAULT NULL;
ALTER TABLE campaigns ADD COLUMN artifact_failed_at TEXT DEFAULT NULL;
ALTER TABLE campaigns ADD COLUMN analysis_failure_reason TEXT DEFAULT NULL;
ALTER TABLE campaigns ADD COLUMN artifact_failure_reason TEXT DEFAULT NULL;

Migration description (for _MIGRATIONS in db.py):

"Campaign completion semantics: add analysis_status, artifact_status, and context_quality to campaigns. Separates measurement completion from analysis and report completion. Existing rows default to NULL for all three (pre-migration campaigns where these states were not tracked). analysis_status and artifact_status are set by runner.py after each phase. context_quality is written at measurement completion from aggregated run context assessments."

Backward compatibility: All new columns default to NULL. Existing complete campaigns show NULL for all three. The list command's display logic treats NULL analysis_status on a complete campaign as measured (with a note for pre-migration rows if desired).

Changes to artifacts table
The artifacts table already exists and has the right schema. The problem is that it is not being consistently written by the report generation code. As part of this remediation, runner.py's post-analysis pipeline must write artifact rows when reports are generated. One row per artifact, per the existing schema.

This is a behavioral change, not a schema change. The write should happen within the try block that currently sets report_ok = True.

No changes to campaigns.status values
pending, running, complete, failed remain unchanged. Their semantics are narrowed (as defined in Section 3) but their string values do not change.

5. Operator-Facing Behavior
quantmap list
Currently shows: campaign_id, run_mode, status, cfg_count, winner, winner_tg, timestamp, report_path.

Changes:

Replace the status column display with the synthesized label from Section 3 (not the raw DB value)
Add a Context column showing context_quality when non-NULL and non-clean: displays a short warning symbol (e.g., ⚠ noisy) for degraded context; blank for clean/NULL
report_path is currently fetched from artifacts table. Once artifact writes are consistently done (see Section 4), this should always be populated when artifact_status = 'complete'
The table should remain compact. The Context column only adds noise when there is something to report. Implementation: COALESCE(context_quality, '') and suppress column content when clean or NULL.

During quantmap run (live run)
No behavioral changes to the measurement phase output.

At the post-measurement analysis stage (currently around line 2323), the runner should emit clearer layer-boundary messaging:

✓ Measurement complete. All 8 configs committed to database.
  Running analysis and scoring...
  ✓ Scoring complete.
  Generating reports...
  ✓ Report written: results/NGL_sweep/report.md

Currently the messaging is present but not clearly layered. The fix is cosmetic but carries an important semantic: if scoring succeeds but report generation fails, the operator sees "Scoring complete" and then the report failure — they know what they have.

quantmap run failure paths
Measurement completes, analysis fails:

✓ Measurement complete. All 8 configs committed to database.
  Running analysis and scoring...
  ✗ Analysis failed: <reason>
  
  Measurement data is safe. Run: quantmap rescore NGL_sweep

The campaign exits nonzero (this is already correct at line 2387–2388). The DB is updated: analysis_status = 'failed', analysis_failure_reason = <reason>, analysis_failed_at = <timestamp>.

Analysis succeeds, report generation fails:

✓ Measurement complete. All 8 configs committed to database.
  Running analysis and scoring...
  ✓ Scoring complete.
  Generating reports...
  ✗ Report generation failed: <reason>
  
  Scores are available. Run: quantmap report NGL_sweep

Exits nonzero. artifact_status = 'failed', artifact_failure_reason = <reason>.

Both succeed:
analysis_status = 'complete', artifact_status = 'complete'. Artifact rows written to artifacts table. Exits zero.

No quantmap status command for MVP
A dedicated status command (showing the full layered status of a single campaign) is a v1.1 item. For MVP, the list command with the synthesized label is sufficient. Operators can see the state they care about without an additional subcommand.

6. Artifact / Report Boundary
Current behavior (the problem)
Report generation is currently called directly from runner.py at lines 2326–2388. The runner imports generate_report and calls it. If it fails, the DB says complete with no persistent record of the failure. If it succeeds, the report path is printed to the console but not guaranteed to be written to the artifacts table.

Proposed behavior
Report generation remains called from runner.py at the same location. The change is in what state is written to the DB:

On analysis success:

conn.execute(
    "UPDATE campaigns SET analysis_status='complete' WHERE id=?",
    (effective_campaign_id,)
)

On analysis failure:

conn.execute(
    """UPDATE campaigns 
       SET analysis_status='failed', 
           analysis_failure_reason=?,
           analysis_failed_at=?
       WHERE id=?""",
    (str(exc), now_iso, effective_campaign_id)
)

On report success:

conn.execute(
    "UPDATE campaigns SET artifact_status='complete' WHERE id=?",
    (effective_campaign_id,)
)
# Write artifact row
conn.execute(
    "INSERT INTO artifacts (campaign_id, artifact_type, path, sha256, created_at) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)",
    (effective_campaign_id, 'report_md', str(report_path), _hash_file(report_path), now_iso)
)

On report failure:

conn.execute(
    """UPDATE campaigns 
       SET artifact_status='failed',
           artifact_failure_reason=?,
           artifact_failed_at=?
       WHERE id=?""",
    (str(exc), now_iso, effective_campaign_id)
)

Each of these uses a new short-lived connection (get_connection()) opened specifically for the status write. This avoids coupling the post-analysis state write to the main measurement connection, which was already closed at line 2299.

Report regeneration
The existing comment at line 2319 says "rescore.py can replay the pipeline at any time" — but there is no rescore.py in the actual codebase visible from what I've read. For MVP, do not create a new subcommand. Instead:

Document the regeneration path in the analysis-failed error message: "Run python -m src.score <campaign_id> to rescore."
This is currently functional — score_campaign() is callable standalone.
A proper quantmap rescore / quantmap report subcommand is a v1.1 item, not MVP.

7. Retry / Resume / Recompute Semantics
This section is a definitional spec, not an implementation plan. Each capability is defined and its current state noted.

Resumable (measurement phase)
Definition: Measurement resumes from the last completed config, within a cycle boundary.

Current state: Implemented via progress.json and the --resume flag. Cycle-level resume drops partial cycles and restarts from request 1. This is correct and should not change.

Which states allow resume:

status = 'running' (interrupted mid-campaign) → always resumable
status = 'complete' → measurement does not need to resume; analysis/artifact may be re-triggerable (see below)
status = 'failed' → possibly resumable depending on where failure occurred; safest to add --force-resume to override the failed state check
What does NOT need to change: The resume mechanism itself is sound. The only gap is that a campaign stuck in status = 'running' due to a crash is visually indistinguishable in list from a campaign actively running. Post-remediation, this is resolved because running means "in progress or interrupted" and the operator can use --resume to continue either way.

Re-scorable (Layer 2)
Definition: The scoring/analysis pipeline can be rerun on existing Layer 1 data.

Current state: score_campaign() in score.py is a standalone function that takes campaign_id and db_path. It can be called independently of runner.py. What it lacks is a CLI entry point.

MVP: No new CLI command. Document the call path in failure messages. Add to v1.1.

v1.1: quantmap rescore <campaign_id> — reruns score_campaign() and updates analysis_status. Must check that campaigns.status = 'complete' before proceeding. Must accept --force to override analysis_status = 'complete' (re-scoring a previously scored campaign).

Re-renderable (Layer 3)
Definition: Reports can be regenerated from existing Layer 1 + Layer 2 data.

Current state: generate_report() in report.py is callable standalone.

MVP: No new CLI command. Document the call path in failure messages.

v1.1: quantmap report <campaign_id> — reruns report generation. Must check that analysis_status = 'complete' first. Updates artifact_status and writes artifact rows.

Attributable later (future)
When the attribution engine (from the attribution MVP spec) is implemented, attribute_campaign() will be callable on any campaign whose measurement data is in the DB. This is inherently a Layer 2 operation and follows the re-scorable semantics: callable standalone, writes to attribution_events table, updates a future attribution_status column.

Exportable later
export.py's run_export() is already standalone and works from the DB. No changes needed for exportability. Any campaign with status = 'complete' (measurement done) can be exported, whether or not analysis succeeded. The export should include analysis_status and artifact_status in the campaign row so the recipient knows what they're receiving.

8. Implementation Strategy
Phase 1 — Minimum safe remediation
Goal: Close the truthfulness gap in completion semantics. No new user-facing commands. Minimal DB changes.

Changes:

Migration 10 — Add analysis_status, artifact_status, context_quality, and the associated timestamp/reason columns to campaigns (as specified in Section 4).

runner.py — Post-analysis state writes — After each post-measurement phase (analysis, report), write the appropriate status column. Each write uses an explicit connection; exceptions are caught and logged rather than raised (the measurement data is safe regardless). See Section 6 for the exact code pattern.

runner.py — Context quality aggregation — After all configs complete measurement (before status = 'complete' is written), aggregate the run context quality across the cycles where context files were captured. The aggregation logic:

Scan results/{campaign_id}/{config_id}_cycle*_run_context.json files
Read assessment.quality from each
Map to a severity ranking: distorted > noisy > mostly_clean > clean
Take the worst-case quality as the campaign-level context_quality
If no context files exist: context_quality = 'unavailable'
Write to campaigns.context_quality
This is a file scan across a small number of files (N_configs × N_cycles, typically ≤ 25). It is fast and non-critical — if it fails, log a warning and proceed with context_quality = NULL.

runner.py — Artifact table write — When generate_report() succeeds, write one row to artifacts table (as specified in Section 6).

list command — Synthesized display — Update list_campaigns() in runner.py to compute the display label from status + analysis_status + artifact_status as defined in Section 3. Add context_quality as a compact warning indicator.

What Phase 1 does not change:

No new CLI commands
No changes to measurement-phase logic
No changes to cycle or config state machines
No changes to score.py, analyze.py, or report.py themselves
Phase 1 success condition: An operator running quantmap list after a campaign where analysis failed sees analysis-failed and a message indicating measurement data is safe. A campaign that completed fully shows complete. Context degradation is visible without digging into files.

Phase 2 — Recompute entry points
Goal: Give operators the ability to recover from Layer 2 and Layer 3 failures without rerunning measurement.

Changes:

quantmap rescore <campaign_id> — CLI subcommand. Checks campaigns.status = 'complete'. Runs score_campaign(). Updates analysis_status. Accepts --force to overwrite existing scores.

quantmap report <campaign_id> — CLI subcommand. Checks analysis_status = 'complete'. Runs generate_report(). Updates artifact_status. Writes artifact row.

quantmap status <campaign_id> — Single-campaign status view. Shows all three layer statuses, context quality, timestamps, and relevant artifact paths. More detail than list. Useful for debugging partial failures.

Phase 2 dependency: Phase 1 must be complete. The new commands read analysis_status and artifact_status to decide what to do, so those columns must exist and be populated.

Phase 3 — Defer
These are genuine future work but should not block Phases 1 and 2:

Granular context quality per-cycle display in explain
Partial measurement success semantics (campaign where some configs crashed mid-cycle but others completed — currently handled adequately by per-cycle invalidation)
Automatic re-score trigger on --resume when analysis_status = 'failed'
Context quality storage in the DB as a proper relational structure (currently proposed as a flat TEXT column on campaigns)
Multi-run/re-run tracking (distinguishing runs that reused the same campaign ID from fresh campaigns)
9. Acceptance Criteria
The following conditions define "good enough" for Phase 1.

AC-1: Truthful list on analysis failure
Test: Run a campaign. Monkey-patch or provoke a failure in score_campaign() (e.g., via a test fixture). Check quantmap list.

Pass: The campaign appears with display label analysis-failed. The raw campaigns.status is complete. The console during the run showed "Measurement data is safe" with a rescore instruction.

AC-2: Truthful list on full success
Test: Run a campaign end-to-end with no failures.

Pass: The campaign appears with display label complete. Both analysis_status and artifact_status are complete in the DB. A row exists in artifacts for the report.

AC-3: Context degradation visible in list
Test: Run a campaign in a noisy environment (search indexer active, or inject a context_quality = 'noisy' value).

Pass: The context_quality column in campaigns is set. list shows a visual indicator for the degraded context alongside the campaign row. Clean runs show nothing additional.

AC-4: Legacy campaigns display correctly
Test: Query quantmap list against a DB that contains pre-migration campaigns (NULL analysis_status).

Pass: Pre-migration campaigns display as measured (NULL analysis_status on a complete campaign). They do not show as complete. There is no crash, no exception, no confusing behavior.

AC-5: Measurement data is never modified by post-measurement code
Test: After a campaign where analysis fails, query the requests, telemetry, and cycles tables.

Pass: All rows are intact and unchanged. The failure in analysis left no trace in Layer 1.

AC-6: Artifact table is populated on successful runs
Test: Run a campaign to full completion. Query SELECT * FROM artifacts WHERE campaign_id = ?.

Pass: At least one row exists for artifact_type = 'report_md' with a valid path. The path points to a file that exists on disk.

AC-7: Report failure causes nonzero exit and correct DB state
Test: Run a campaign. Provoke a failure in generate_report(). Check exit code and DB.

Pass: Exit code is nonzero. analysis_status = 'complete', artifact_status = 'failed', artifact_failure_reason is populated. The scores table is populated (analysis succeeded before report failed).

AC-8: context_quality is 'unavailable' when no run context files exist
Test: Run a campaign in an environment where create_run_context() fails for all cycles (provoke the non-fatal path at runner.py line 1475–1478).

Pass: campaigns.context_quality = 'unavailable' in the DB. No crash. The campaign completes normally.

AC-9: Synthesized display label is deterministic
Test: Given the same status, analysis_status, and artifact_status values, list always produces the same display label.

Pass: The display label mapping (Section 3) is implemented as a pure function with no external state dependencies. The same input always produces the same label.

This spec is scoped to the minimum changes needed to make QuantMap's completion semantics truthful. It does not redesign the measurement pipeline, the state machine for cycles and configs, or the report content. Implementation should proceed in the phase order specified: close the truthfulness gap first, then add recompute entry points, then refine.